DOCUMENT();    # This should be the first executable line in the problem.

loadMacros('PGstandard.pl', 'PGML.pl', 'PGstatisticsmacros.pl', 'PGcourse.pl');

$a1 = Real(random(19, 25, 1));

@p = map { random($a1 - 5, $a1 + 5) } (1 .. 10);

($min, $Q1, $median, $Q3, $max) = five_point_summary(@p);

BEGIN_PGML
Find the five-number summary for the following 10 values:

[``` [@ join(', ', @p)@] ```]

*NOTE:* Different books define the word "quartile" in different ways which can lead to somewhat different results.   In this exercise we define the first quartile to be the median of the bottom half of the data set, and the third quartile to be the median of the top half.  

a) Find the minimum: [_]{$min}{5}

b) Find [`Q_{1}`]: [_]{$Q1}{5}

c) Find the median: [_]{$median}{5}

d) Find [`Q_{3}`]: [_]{$Q3}{5}

e) Find the maximum: [_]{$max}{5}
END_PGML

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
First, it is helpful to have the data sorted or 

[``` [@ join(', ', num_sort(@p)) @] ```]

a) min = [$min]

b) [`Q_1`] is the median of the first half of the data or [$Q1]

c) The median is the middle value of [$median]

d) [`Q_3`] is the median of the  top half of the data or [$Q3]

e) max = [$max]

END_PGML_SOLUTION

ENDDOCUMENT();
